`Australia/ACT` is an old deprecated name in the [IANA database (*tzdata*)][1] and does not refer to [Australian Central Time][2].  It instead refers to [Australian Capital Territory][3], which is in the same time zone as [Sydney][4].

Try `Australia/Adelaide` or `Australia/Broken_Hill` for time zones refering to [Australian Central Time][2].


Example code.

    LocalDateTime ldt = LocalDateTime.of ( 2019 , 03 , 31 , 13 , 0 , 0 , 0 );
    System.out.println ( &quot;Offsets for: &quot; + ldt );

    List &lt; ZoneId &gt; zones = 
            List.of ( 
                ZoneId.of ( &quot;Australia/Adelaide&quot; ) , 
                ZoneId.of ( &quot;Australia/Broken_Hill&quot; ) 
            )
    ;
    for ( ZoneId zone : zones )
    {
        ZoneOffset offset = zone.getRules ().getOffset ( ldt );
        System.out.println ( &quot;zone: &quot; + zone.toString () + &quot; has offset: &quot; + offset.toString () );
    }

When run in Java 13 (from AdoptOpenJDK):

&gt;Offsets for: 2019-03-31T13:00

&gt;zone: Australia/Adelaide has offset: +10:30

&gt;zone: Australia/Broken_Hill has offset: +10:30

Tip: For full list of real time zones, consult a fresh copy of [*tzdata*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tz_database). More conveniently, consult [Wikipedia for a list of time zones][5], though the list may be outdated. 


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tz_database
  [2]: https://www.timeanddate.com/time/zones/act-australia
  [3]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Capital_Territory
  [4]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sydney
  [5]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tz_database_time_zones

